## 6. DUPLICATE / REPETITIVE FILE DETECTION

This is content-aware. File names are irrelevant. Two differently named files with the same or very similar content are flagged.

### 6a. Image Duplicate Detection
- Tool: `imagehash` (pHash — perceptual hash)
- Method: Compute pHash for every photo. Compare all pairs. If Hamming distance < `duplicate_hash_threshold` → duplicate pair found.
- Result: Both files go to **review** bucket with log note: `DUPLICATE of [filename] (hash distance: X)`

### 6b. Video Duplicate Detection
- Tool: OpenCV + imagehash
- Method: Extract `frame_sample_count` keyframes from each video. Compute pHash for each keyframe. Compare keyframe hashes across all video pairs. If >70% of keyframes match → duplicate.
- Result: Both files go to **review** with log note: `DUPLICATE of [filename] (XX% keyframe match)`

### 6c. Audio Duplicate Detection
- Tool: librosa
- Method: Compute chromagram fingerprint for each audio file. Compare fingerprints using cosine similarity. Above 0.95 similarity → duplicate.
- Result: Both files go to **review** with log note: `DUPLICATE of [filename] (audio fingerprint match)`

### 6d. Duplicate Handling Rule
- Never auto-delete either file
- Both go to `/review/` regardless of their QC scores
- The log clearly states which file is the suspected duplicate of which

